  <brief_title>Evaluation of the Safety and Efficacy of Memantine as Adjunctive Treatment in Schizophrenia Patients</brief_title>
  <official_title>A Double-Blind, Placebo-Controlled Evaluation of the Safety and Efficacy of Memantine as Adjunctive Treatment to Atypical Antipsychotics in Schizophrenia Patients With Persistent Residual Symptoms</official_title>
  <sponsors>
    <lead_sponsor>
      <agency>Forest Laboratories</agency>
      <agency_class>Industry</agency_class>
    </lead_sponsor>
  </sponsors>
  <source>Forest Laboratories</source>
  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Standard antipsychotic drug regimens do not fully address the impact of cognitive symptoms
      associated with schizophrenia. The NMDA receptor has been connected to the pathophysiology of
      schizophrenia. Memantine is an uncompetitive NMDA receptor antagonist. It is hypothesized
      that adjunctive therapy with memantine will reduce NMDA receptor hyperactivity, improving
      signal to noise ratio and thereby improving cognitive symptoms.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
